CHANGELOG
=========

Port of checkpassword-0.90 (D. J. Bernstein) to build on Debian 13 (trixie)
with GCC 15 / glibc 2.x / libxcrypt.

Root cause
----------
GCC 15 defaults to the C23 standard, in which an empty parameter list "()"
means "(void)" (zero arguments) instead of the old K&R "unspecified
arguments". This breaks the many empty-prototype declarations DJB relies on.
Additionally, modern glibc defines `errno` as a macro, and libxcrypt no
longer ships a `libcrypt.so` symlink unless libcrypt-dev is installed.

Changes
-------
- conf-cc
  Added compiler flags: -std=gnu17 -fcommon -Wno-implicit-int
  -Wno-implicit-function-declaration -Wno-int-conversion
  -Wno-incompatible-pointer-types
  -std=gnu17 restores the pre-C23 meaning of empty prototypes; the -Wno-*
  flags downgrade errors that GCC 14+ promoted from warnings.

- error.h
  Replaced `extern int errno;` with `#include <errno.h>`.
  `errno` is a macro in modern glibc, so the extern declaration is invalid.

- exit.h
  Replaced `extern void _exit();` with `#include <unistd.h>`.

- readwrite.h
  Replaced `extern int read(); extern int write();` with
  `#include <unistd.h>`. The old int-returning prototypes conflict with the
  ssize_t signatures in unistd.h.

- checkpassword.c
  Replaced `extern char *crypt();` with a full prototype
  `extern char *crypt(const char *, const char *);` so the 2-argument call
  is accepted under C23 rules, without depending on <crypt.h>.

- Makefile (crypt.lib rule)
  Added a fallback: if `-lcrypt` linking fails (libcrypt-dev not installed,
  so no libcrypt.so symlink), fall back to the versioned shared object
  /usr/lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libcrypt.so.1.
  Cleaner alternative: install libcrypt-dev and revert this line, letting the
  autodetection emit `-lcrypt` on its own.

Result
------
Builds cleanly: checkpassword, install, instcheck.
Verified: `./checkpassword` with no args exits 2; binary links libcrypt.so.1.

Security fixes
--------------
- checkpassword.c: check crypt() return value for NULL.
  Original code assumed crypt() never fails. Modern libxcrypt returns NULL
  on malformed salt/setting strings — e.g. locked accounts ("!", "*") or the
  shadow placeholder "x" — causing strcmp(NULL, stored) to crash with
  SIGSEGV. Denial of service, remotely triggerable by submitting any locked
  username. Now exits 1 instead.

- checkpassword.c: equalize timing for unknown users.
  Previously an unknown username exited immediately, while a valid username
  ran a full crypt() (~yescrypt cost). The timing difference allowed remote
  enumeration of valid logins. Both failure paths (unknown user, no stored
  hash) now run crypt() against a fixed dummy yescrypt setting
  ("$y$j9T$...", the Debian default cost) before exiting.

- checkpassword.c: wipe the login/password buffer with explicit_bzero().
  The original zeroing loop was a dead store the compiler is allowed to
  optimize away, leaving the plaintext password in memory. explicit_bzero()
  cannot be elided. The buffer is now also wiped on the failure paths above.

- checkpassword.c: clear errno before getpwnam()/getspnam()/getuserpw().
  These functions do not reliably set errno when the user is simply not
  found; a stale ETXTBSY from an earlier syscall could turn "unknown user"
  (exit 1) into a spurious temporary failure (exit 111).

- gen_allocdefs.h, alloc.c: integer overflow guards in the allocators.
  The stralloc growth arithmetic (base + n + n/8, n + len, n * sizeof(type))
  and the alloc() alignment round-up (marked "XXX: could overflow" by the
  author) could wrap around unsigned int for sizes near 4GB, producing an
  undersized allocation followed by a heap overflow. Requests that would
  wrap are now rejected as allocation failures. Not reachable in
  checkpassword itself (input is capped at 512 bytes), fixed for hardening.

Tests
-----
- test_unit.c: assert-based unit tests for the library primitives
  (str_len/str_chr/str_start, byte_copy/byte_diff, stralloc building and
  growth across reallocation, allocator integer-overflow guards).
- test_checkpassword.sh: exit-code tests for the binary (no-arg, empty,
  malformed and oversized input, unknown user, wrong password — the last
  one exercising the crypt() NULL path when shadow is unreadable).
- Makefile: new "make test" target builds and runs both.

Verified: real user + wrong password exits 1 (previously SIGSEGV via NULL
crypt() result when shadow is unreadable); unknown user exits 1 after a
dummy crypt() with the same cost parameters as /etc/shadow defaults;
allocator unit test confirms sane sizes still succeed and wrap-inducing
sizes (0xFFFFFFF0, n+len wrap, growth-math wrap) are rejected without
crashing.
